s of recent information we gathered from some health facilities in The Gambia that the problem of malaria in the country is decreasing fast. While this is very welcome news, it presents new challenges which require follow up study to describe in detail the features of the change and how to monitor the situation well.||The changes in malaria situation may also require changes in the way malaria control activities are currently being designed and carried out in the country. It will also have effect on the types of malaria research we do as an institution. This is because to be able to assess the impact of the ongoing malaria control activities, monitor the changes in malaria burden over time and determine how new drugs, vaccines or strategies that will be developed in the near future will be tested. We need new and current information on malaria in the Gambia. We are therefore doing a series of surveys in different age groups, health facilities and communities to gather the most current information on malaria in The Gambia to help sustain the achievements both in malaria research and control.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>Introduction: Malaria epidemiology and intervention studies have been conducted at various times and places in The Gambia, during which time malaria has become less prevalent, although it is still one of the leading causes of morbidity and mortality in the country.||Rationale: Recent analysis of retrospective data from several health facilities in the Gambia suggests a marked decrease in malaria burden. There is the need to confirm this finding as it has implications for the implementation of control measures and design of malaria intervention studies. To efficiently evaluate the impact of the expanding malaria control programme, monitor the declining malaria trends and assess novel control tools and strategies that may appear in the future, robust indices of the current malaria epidemiology are required. The available malaria indicators, although important, are constrained in determining the characteristics of the emerging trend. Additional information on areas and populations at risk will therefore help prioritise malaria control and research activities.||Objectives: The study seeks to characterize the changes in the epidemiology of malaria and transmission intensity in ecologically diverse settings in the Gambia. Additionally, it will evaluate the usefulness of different malaria indices and methods for monitoring the declining trend over time and space.||Age stratified, seasonal surveys in a representative sample selected randomly from six ecologically diverse areas and health centres were conducted during the peak malaria season (September to November 2008) and during the dry season (March to May 2009). Demographic, clinical and socio-economic information were collected during the surveys. Finger prick blood specimens for malaria parasite detection, haemoglobin determination and filter paper specimen for anti-malaria antibodies detection were collected. Data for cost analysis comparing different estimates of malariometric indices based on survey methods in the community and health centres will also be computed.||Expected outcomes: 1. Current data on malaria endemicity, transmission intensity and malaria attributable proportions. 2. The utility of sero-prevalence of malaria specific antibodies for monitoring transmission intensity.3. The usefulness of health facility surveys as a method to describe and monitor area specific malaria epidemiology.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2011-03-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2008-06-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>EXPENDITURE_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>4404112</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminat